<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- President Bill Clinton announced Monday that a new surge of
money into government coffers will allow him to propose a balanced
budget this year, the first time in nearly three decades that a
president has presented Congress an annual spending plan with no
red ink.
</P>
<P>
-- House Speaker Newt Gingrich Monday proposed the creation of
a national commission to reform Social Security and said he hopes
Congress can establish a new retirement system sometime in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- In a bizarre beginning to what promises to be a highly
unusual proceeding, the trial of the accused Unabom killer,
Theodore J. Kaczynski, was halted just before it got under way on
Monday morning, when Kaczynski said he had "very important"
complaints about his lawyers.
</P>
<P>
-- In Denver, Colorado, prosecutors invoked images of the dead,
and defense lawyers invoked a biblical tale of mercy as they made
their final arguments Monday over whether Terry L. Nichols should
be executed for his role in the Oklahoma City bombing.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- The FDA issued rules to regulate the advertising and
marketing practices of pharmacy benefit-management companies, many
of which have been bought up by drug makers. Critics warn
patients' health could be jeopardized if the firms use the
benefits units to push health-care providers to switch to their
products.
</P>
<P>
USA Today:
</P>
<P>
-- Volkswagen's New Beetle -- styled to appeal to nostalgic
baby boomers -- goes on sale in March with a lower-than-expected
price aimed at younger buyers. 
</P>
